  "doc_id": "29060",
  "text": "The lack of a statistically significant change of the mean T2 relaxation time in two of the boys on therapy might reflect the ability of steroids to diminish the natural progression of DMD. Prior clinical studies have shown a relatively longer steroid effect in a group of patients with DMD and who also had the N 363S polymorphism, as compared to a non-carrier group [CITATION_1] . Although none of the patients in our study were evaluated for this specific gene, we suggest that some boys achieved a relatively stable disease state on steroid therapy. Kissel et al. [CITATION_2] showed a significant decrease in mononuclear cells in the muscle biopsies from patients with DMD and who were treated with steroids, as compared to an untreated group, and this suggested the steroids reversed the inflammatory changes. In four children in our study, a decrease in mean T2 relaxation time was seen while they were on steroid therapy. This finding might reflect a decrease in muscle inflammation, despite that there were no identifiable changes on conventional MRI or on clinical assessment.",
